    "synopsis": "[A] 1 Enoch 56 presents a prophetic vision of eschatological judgment executed through invading armies from the east, specifically the Parthians and Medes. The chapter divides into two movements: (1) the return of the dispersed righteous to Jerusalem (vv. 5-8), and (2) the stirring up of eastern armies who will trample the land of the elect before being destroyed in the valley of judgment. [B] This imagery draws on the prophetic tradition of God using foreign armies as instruments of judgment (Isaiah 10:5-6, Jeremiah 25:9), but here applied to the final eschatological conflict. [C] The Parthian Empire (247 BC – AD 224) represented Rome's most formidable eastern rival, and Jewish apocalyptic literature frequently cast them in the role of God's avenging rod against the oppressive western empire. The chapter reflects Second Temple expectations that the Messiah's coming would be preceded by catastrophic warfare involving the great powers surrounding Israel.",
    
